17:18.121 --> 17:19.861
What does...

17:26.796 --> 17:27.956
Thirty?

17:28.840 --> 17:29.955
Everybody lies.

17:33.637 --> 17:35.969
Higher or lower?

17:40.352 --> 17:42.934
Followed your advice
and took the night off.

17:43.021 --> 17:44.261
It seems to have
done you some good.

17:44.356 --> 17:45.687
Mmm-hmm.

17:51.321 --> 17:53.277
Where's my husband?

17:56.785 --> 17:57.865
So he just walked out?

17:57.953 --> 18:00.490
All of the shift nurses
had their hands full
with a double code.

18:00.580 --> 18:02.286
HOUSE: Perfectly
reasonable explanation.

18:02.374 --> 18:04.831
Same thing happened to me.
Couldn't find my keys
for days.

18:05.460 --> 18:08.247
The police
have been notified,
I have staff searching.

18:08.338 --> 18:10.579
You told me
it was okay to leave.

18:11.383 --> 18:12.498
I'm sorry.

18:12.592 --> 18:15.800
He has Alzheimer's!
It's freezing outside!

18:15.887 --> 18:17.502
And he's sick!

18:17.597 --> 18:19.804
I mean,
you don't even know
what it is yet, do you?

18:19.891 --> 18:21.882
The plasmapheresis
hasn't had time to work,

18:21.977 --> 18:23.433
but TTP is
our most likely...

18:23.520 --> 18:24.976
Okay, I have to
go look for him.

18:26.356 --> 18:29.519
Hey. Don't be an ass.
Can't you see she's upset?

18:29.609 --> 18:31.520
No, she's guilty.

18:32.362 --> 18:36.526
Instead of being at
her husband's side,
she was under you.

18:36.616 --> 18:38.197
Okay. That's...

18:38.285 --> 18:41.072
Yeah, he already
said I was an ass.

18:41.913 --> 18:44.575
Personally,
I applaud your decision
to step down off your cross

18:44.666 --> 18:46.873
and get on with your life,
but your misplaced guilt

18:46.960 --> 18:48.245
is shutting down
your brain.

18:48.336 --> 18:51.749
We need you to sit, focus,
and answer our questions.

18:59.848 --> 19:02.134
So it's 6:00 am,
patient wakes up,

19:02.976 --> 19:05.809
and the first thing
he sees...

19:05.937 --> 19:09.771
In moments of confusion,
Alzheimer's patients
regress to old routines.

19:09.858 --> 19:12.190
HOUSE: So what would
your husband do
on a Saturday morning?

19:12.569 --> 19:15.106
Nothing. Be at home.

19:15.196 --> 19:17.482
What about a year ago,
five years, or 10?

19:18.408 --> 19:19.693
I don't know.

19:20.702 --> 19:22.192
He trained for
a marathon once.

19:22.287 --> 19:25.074
Soccer practice.
We took a cooking class.

19:26.666 --> 19:30.079
The soccer trophy you were
telling me about, it's gone.

19:30.170 --> 19:31.250
Where was practice?

19:31.338 --> 19:34.080
It was close to here,
on Chesterfield.

19:48.688 --> 19:51.304
Okay, he comes,
he thinks he's waiting
for practice.

19:51.441 --> 19:53.557
He'd want to get out
of the wind,

19:53.651 --> 19:56.142
but somewhere
he could see
the kids arrive.

19:56.946 --> 19:58.607
There.

20:00.992 --> 20:02.698
Over here!

20:12.170 --> 20:13.706
On three.
One, two, three.

20:18.343 --> 20:19.378
Nothing.

20:19.469 --> 20:21.380
Not dead till
he's warm and dead.

20:29.521 --> 20:30.806
Get him to the ICU.

20:30.897 --> 20:32.683
Start him on
extracorporeal circulation.

20:32.816 --> 20:35.182
That'll raise his
temperature too quickly,
it'll cause acidosis.

20:35.318 --> 20:37.024
We can deal with
his metabolism crashing.

20:37.153 --> 20:39.189
We can't
reverse brain damage
if we go too slowly.

20:39.322 --> 20:41.062
Either way, if we don't
get his temperature
above 95,

20:41.157 --> 20:42.237
it's not gonna matter.

20:42.325 --> 20:44.816
Multiple warm lavage
is safer.

20:47.330 --> 20:49.195
Do what House says.

20:57.549 --> 21:01.588
NATALIE:
He has no heartbeat,
he's not breathing.

21:03.596 --> 21:04.927
How can he not
be dead?

21:05.682 --> 21:08.799
Body slows down
when it cools,
but it doesn't fully stop.

21:08.893 --> 21:11.976
We're warming his blood
outside of his body
and then putting it back.

21:12.063 --> 21:13.439
It'll raise his
temperature enough

21:13.523 --> 21:15.514
that his heart
should naturally start.

21:15.942 --> 21:17.728
Then we can shock it
back into rhythm.

21:17.861 --> 21:19.852
And if it doesn't start?

21:22.615 --> 21:23.866
Then there's
nothing we can do.

21:31.082 --> 21:32.868
You think
it's possible he knew
what he was doing?

21:33.877 --> 21:37.335
Like some part of him
gets what he's putting
his wife through,

21:37.422 --> 21:38.912
so he tried to...
Kill himself?

21:40.049 --> 21:42.040
It's what I'd do
if I were him.

21:42.135 --> 21:43.966
At least I Wish I would.

21:45.388 --> 21:46.969
I meant run away.

21:47.724 --> 21:50.010
You think
you should kill yourself
if you become a burden

21:50.101 --> 21:51.181
to the people
who love you?

21:51.269 --> 21:54.978
If you really loved
them back, then yes.

21:57.442 --> 21:59.307
That's really dark.

22:00.445 --> 22:02.231
It's not naive.

22:03.740 --> 22:07.779
I just believe
people are capable of more
than you do, apparently.

22:08.369 --> 22:09.905
(MONITOR BEEPS)

22:09.996 --> 22:11.236
We've got
brain activity.

22:13.458 --> 22:16.746
Temp's at 93.
His heart should
start soon.

22:21.925 --> 22:24.382
My dad left me alone
to care for
my alcoholic mom

22:24.469 --> 22:25.709
and raise
my baby sister.

22:25.803 --> 22:27.259
I was just a teenager.

22:28.181 --> 22:29.967
I spent half of my time
changing diapers

22:30.099 --> 22:32.260
and the other half
cleaning up my mom's vomit.

22:33.811 --> 22:35.392
But it must
have been important

22:35.480 --> 22:37.596
that you stayed
for both of them.

22:38.608 --> 22:40.519
Mom died
after a few years.

22:40.610 --> 22:44.228
It was ugly and painful,
and she went
with me hating her.

22:44.322 --> 22:46.563
My sister
ended up drinking
half of her life away

22:46.658 --> 22:49.274
and hating me
because I couldn't help.

22:49.369 --> 22:51.109
After Mom,
